  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_729",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Private Set Intersection in the Internet Setting From Lightweight Oblivious PRF",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Melissa Chase",
        "email": "melissac@microsoft",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Peihan Miao",
        "email": "compeihan@berkeley",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We present a new protocol for two-party private set intersection (PSI) with semi-honest security in the plain model and one-sided malicious security in the random oracle model. Our protocol achieves a better balance between computation and communication than existing PSI protocols. Specifically, our protocol is the fastest in networks with moderate bandwidth (e.g., 30 - 100 Mbps). Considering the monetary cost (proposed by Pinkas et al. in CRYPTO 2019) to run the protocol on a cloud computing service, our protocol also compares favorably.\n\nUnderlying our PSI protocol is a new lightweight multi-point oblivious pesudorandom function (OPRF) protocol based on oblivious transfer (OT) extension. We believe this new protocol may be of independent interest.",
    "keywords": [
      "Private Set Intersection",
      "Oblivious Pseudorandom Function",
      "OT Extension",
      "Secure Computation"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "Published by the IACR in CRYPTO 2020",
    "last_updated": "2020-08-11",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
